'''''Kala''''' is the second [[studio album]] by British musician [[M.I.A. (artist)|M.I.A.]], released in August 2007.  The album features musical styles ranging from [[dance music]] to [[alternative hip hop]] and makes extensive use of ethnic sounds such as that of the [[urumee]], a drum native to [[India]].  It was mainly written and produced by M.I.A. and [[Switch (DJ)|Switch]], and features contributions from [[Timbaland]], [[Diplo (DJ)|Diplo]], [[Afrikan Boy]] and [[The Wilcannia Mob]].

M.I.A. named the album after her mother, in contrast to her first album ''[[Arular]]'', which was named after her father, and stated that her mother's struggles in life are a major theme of the recording.  She began recording the album in early 2006 and worked on the tracks in various locations around the world, including [[India]] and [[Trinidad]].  Planned sessions in the United States failed to occur, after M.I.A. was refused a long-term work [[Visa (document)|visa]] to enter the country.

''Kala'' was ranked as one of the best albums of the year by several publications, although others gave it a poor review.  It reached number&nbsp;18 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, 172 places higher than ''Arular'', and topped the magazine's [[Dance/Electronic Albums|Top Electronic Albums]] chart.  In the United Kingdom it reached number&nbsp;39 on the [[UK Albums Chart]], 59 places higher than her debut album.  ''Kala'' has spawned the [[Single (music)|singles]] "[[Boyz (song)|Boyz]]", "[[Jimmy (song)|Jimmy]]" and "[[Paper Planes]]".

==Composition and recording==
British musician M.I.A. (Mathangi "Maya" Arulpragasam) had released her debut album ''[[Arular]]'' in 2005, which achieved critical acclaim and sold 130,000 copies.<ref name="via" />  Plans for a second album were first revealed when she spoke later that year of her intention to work with American producer [[Timbaland]].  At one point it was anticipated that he would produce the bulk of the album.<ref name="CC" /><ref name="modemand">{{cite video |people=Leah Miller (Presenter), M.I.A. (Interviewee)| title= MuchMusic Much on Demand: M.I.A. Transcript Sep 2005| url=http://www.muchmusic.com/music/artists/transcripts.asp?artist=1213 | publisher = [[MuchMusic]]'s ''[[Much on Demand]]'', [[CTVglobemedia]] |medium=TV-Series|date=2005|location=[[Toronto]]| dateformat=dmy|accessdate=24 August 2007}}</ref>  However, she was unable to gain a long-term work [[Visa (document)|visa]] to enter the U.S., reportedly due to her family's connections with guerrillas in [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name="via">{{cite web |title= M.I.A. doesn<U+2019>t need a visa, just inspiration| url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/20379484/ | publisher=[[NBC Universal]]/[[Microsoft]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=4 February 2009|date=21 August 2007}}</ref>  This led to conflicts between the two artists' schedules and meant that Timbaland's involvement was restricted to a poorly received guest verse on the track "Come Around".<ref name="CC">{{cite web|url=http://thephoenix.com/Boston/Music/46609-Culture-clash/?page=2|title=Culture clash|first=Nick|last=Sylvester|accessdate=15 September 2009|date=5 September 200&|dateformat=dmy|work=[[The Phoenix (newspaper)|The Boston Phoenix]]}}</ref>  M.I.A. instead opted to record the album at a variety of locations around the world,<ref name="via" /> beginning by travelling to India following the last date of her [[Arular Tour]] in Japan in February 2006.<ref name="urb" />

{{listen
|pos=right 
 | filename     = Bird Flu - MIA.ogg
 | title        = M.I.A. "Bird Flu" (2007)
 | description  = Short clip of "Bird Flu" showing the track's use of [[urumee]] drums.
