}}
She initially travelled to India to meet [[A. R. Rahman]], but found it hard to communicate her ideas to him and the planned musical collaboration did not take place.<ref name="miafadermag07"/>  Rahman did, however, provide M.I.A. with a number of contacts and allow her to use his studio, where 22 members of drumming group The Tapes were recorded for ''Kala''.<ref name="logic">{{ cite web | url=http://www.apple.com/logicstudio/in-action/switch/?sr=hotnews | title=Dave <U+201C>Switch<U+201D> Taylor: Producing M.I.A. | first=Joe|last=Cellini | publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=18 December 2008 }}</ref><ref name="tapes">{{ cite web | url=http://emusician.com/remixmag/artists_interviews/musicians/mia_switch_diplo_kala/ | title=Out on a whim <U+2013> M.I.A., aka Maya Arulpragasam, Switch and Diplo on recording Kala | last=Moayeri|first= Lily | work=Remix  | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=19 December 2008  }}</ref>  Producer [[Switch (DJ)|Switch]], who had initially travelled to India purely to engineer the planned sessions, ultimately became involved in the composition of several tracks for the album.<ref name="miafadermag07" />  A visit to [[Angola]] to work with DJ Znobia was cancelled after Znobia was involved in a car accident,<ref name="miafadermag07" /> but M.I.A. was able to record in [[Trinidad]], [[Liberia]], [[Jamaica]] and Australia.<ref name="rollingstone"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://spin-cdnsrc.texterity.com/spin/200812/?pg=65|title=M.I.A.: POW!|first=Lorraine|last=Ali|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=15 September 2009|dateformat=dmy|date=December 2008}}</ref>  She and Switch relied heavily on [[Logic Pro]], a [[digital audio workstation]] produced by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], and were able to capture vocals and background sounds outside the traditional studio environment, using a microphone and Switch's laptop.<ref name="logic"/><ref name="tapes"/> The album features guest vocals from [[Afrikan Boy]], [[The Wilcannia Mob]], and Timbaland, and further collaborations with Switch, [[Blaqstarr]], Morganics and [[Diplo (DJ)|Diplo]].<ref name="AM">{{cite article|first=Andy|last=Kellman | title= M.I.A.: Kala <U+2013> Overview| url= http://allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:gnfexzrgldhe | publisher=[[Allmusic]] | year=2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=31 July 2007}}</ref>  She likened the process of recording the album to "making a big old [[marble cake]] with lots of different countries and influences. Then you slice it up and call each slice a song".<ref name="miafadermag07">{{cite article |last=Wagner|first= Alex| title= Life in Exile| url= http://www.thefader.com/2007/08/07/video-interview-mia-jimmy/ | work = [[The Fader]] | date=8 July 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=29 December 2007}}</ref>

==Music and lyrics==
[[Image:AfrikanBoyMIA.jpg|thumb|right|240px|alt=A man wearing an African-style hat, sunglasses, and a large gold chain, and holding a microphone.  In the background a woman in brightly coloured clothing and sunglasses is also holding a microphone and is waving one hand in the air|[[Afrikan Boy]] performing live with M.I.A. in France.  He provided vocals for the track "Hussel".]]
''Kala'' is named after M.I.A.'s mother, in contrast to her previous album, ''[[Arular]]'', which was named after her father.<ref>{{cite web | title=M.I.A. : Kala| url= http://drownedinsound.com/releases/11132/reviews/2310992- | publisher= [[Drowned in Sound]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=15 September 2009|date=23 December 2007|first=Sam|last=Lewis}}</ref>  She contends that ''Arular'' was a "masculine" album, but that ''Kala'' "is about my mum and her struggle<U+2013>how do you work, feed your children, nurture them and give them the power of information?"<ref name="urb">{{cite article | last=Hawkins|first=Si|title= M.I.A.: World Party| url= http://web.archive.org/web/20071013164618/http://www.urb.com/features/183/MIAWorldParty.php?PageId=2 | work = [[URB (magazine)|URB]] | date=17 May 2006| dateformat=dmy|accessdate=24 May 2007}}</ref><ref name="miapw">{{cite article | title= What's Up With M.I.A.| url= http://web.archive.org/web/20071013165645/http://philadelphiaweekly.com/view.php?id=12933  | work = [[Philadelphia Weekly]] | date=6 September 2006 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref>  She further summed the album up as "shapes, colours, Africa, street, power, bitch, nu world, and brave."<ref>{{cite article | last=Empire|first=Kitty| title= 10 essential albums for Spring| url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/theobserver/2007/mar/11/featuresreview.review | work=[[The Observer]]|date=11 March 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=7 April 2007}}</ref>

The tracks "[[Boyz (song)|Boyz]]" and "Bird Flu" use [[urumee]] drums, a signature instrument of the [[gaana]] music of [[Tamil Nadu]], with which M.I.A. was familiar from her time spent living in Sri Lanka.  She later worked on these tracks in Trinidad, where she absorbed influences from the country's love of [[soca music]].<ref name="miafadermag07"/><ref name="villagevoicemia"/><ref name="miaexclaimkala07"/>  The lyrics of "Boyz" deal with the artist's time in Jamaica, and reference Jamaican dance moves.<ref name="miafadermag07"/>  The song "Hussel" began as an image in M.I.A.'s head of [[refugees]] being smuggled in boats, which she expressed musically by imagining how "if they banged that beat on the side of a boat, what would it sound like?  That's why it's all [[echo (phenomenon)|echo-y]] and [[submarine|submarine-y]]".<ref name="miafadermag07"/>  "World Town" used instrumentation from the temple music she recalled waking up to as a child in Sri Lanka.<ref name="miafadermag07"/>  After playing the track to children in Liberia, she expressed a desire to record a video for the song there.<ref name="miafadermag07"/>  M.I.A.'s "flat, unaffected vocals and delivery of lyrics" on some songs drew comparisons to British [[post-punk]] bands such as [[Delta 5]] and [[The Slits]].  She says it "was just what was happening to me naturally...I wanted it to be difficult and raw and not get into it so much".<ref name="villagevoicemia"/>

[[Afrikan Boy]], an exponent of [[grime (music)|grime]], a UK-based genre of [[urban music]], provided vocals on the song "Hussel".  M.I.A. opted to work with him because she felt that he seemed comfortable with his identity as a "real immigrant" and because his background was different to that of most [[Master of Ceremonies#Hip_hop_culture|MCs]] in the genre.<ref name="miaexclaimkala07"/>  She had originally planned to include "Mango Pickle Down River"<U+2014>her remix of [[The Wilcannia Mob]]'s song "Down River"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/11/29/1038386308756.html|title=The Wilcannia mob|date=29 November 2002|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=16 March 2010}}</ref><U+2014>on a [[mix-tape]], but chose to include it on the album because she felt it was rare to hear the "[[Aboriginal music|aboriginal voice]]" in recorded music,<ref name="miaexclaimkala07"/> and described opening track "Bamboo Banga" as having a "bamboo-stick beat, [[house (music)|house-y]] feel".<ref name="miaexclaimkala07">{{cite web | last= Lindsay|first=Cam| title= M.I.A.| work= [[Exclaim!]]| url= http://www.exclaim.ca/articles/multiarticlesub.aspx?csid1=114&csid2=946&fid1=27365| month= September | year= 2007 |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=6 March 2008}}</ref>  The song "[[Jimmy (song)|Jimmy]]" was included as a tribute to her mother and is M.I.A.'s version of an old [[Bollywood]] film track to which she used to dance at parties as a child.<ref name="villagevoicemia">{{cite article |last=Breihan|first= Tom| title= Status Ain't Hood interviews M.I.A.| url= http://blogs.villagevoice.com/statusainthood/archives/2007/07/status_aint_hoo_28.php | work = [[The Village Voice]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=6 March 2008|date=18 July 2007}}</ref>  Despite the involvement of [[Baltimore club]] musician Blaqstarr, "The Turn" turned out to be the album's only ballad, and the track has been described as the least like [[club music]].<ref name="miaexclaimkala07"/>  "20 Dollar" was written about the relative ease of buying [[AK-47]]s in war-torn [[Liberia]].<ref>{{cite web | title= Track by Track : M.I.A.|  publisher=[[VH1]]|first=Jonathan|last=Durbin|url= http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1567706/20070823/mia__4_.jhtml | date=23 August 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=23 December 2008}}</ref>  "XR2" recalls part of the artist's life growing up with [[rave music]] in early 1990s London,<ref name="miaexclaimkala07"/> while the song "[[Paper Planes]]" jokingly plays on M.I.A.'s problems with visas and certain perceptions of immigrants.<ref>{{cite web | title= M.I.A. Strike, Match, Light, Fire| publisher=[[MTV]]|url= http://www.mtv.com/overdrive/?id=1574938&vid=190780 | date=3 December 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=6 March 2008}}</ref>

==Artwork==
The album's packaging includes photographs taken by M.I.A. herself and others in [[Liberia]] and [[Jamaica]].<ref name="discogs">Track listing and credits as per liner notes for ''Kala'' album</ref>  The cover artwork to ''Kala'', designed by M.I.A., features neon [[fractal]] patterns and repeated slogans, including "Fight On! Fight On! Fight On!", which surrounds her image on the front cover.<ref name="mia02">{{cite web | first=Dan|last=Nishimoto|title= M.I.A. : Kala| url= http://www.prefixmag.com/reviews/mia/kala/16147/ | publisher = Prefix | date=21 August 2007| dateformat=dmy|accessdate=10 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first=Sharifa|last=Love|title= M.I.A. <U+2013> Kala| url= http://www.spheremagazine.com/551/mia-kala | work = Sphere | date=9 October 2007| dateformat=dmy|accessdate=10 December 2008}}</ref>  The cover was considered garish, prompting ''[[The Village Voice]]'' to comment "Maybe one day [she'll] make an album cover that it doesn't hurt to look at".<ref name="villagevoicemia" />  Additional graphics for the album were provided by English fashion designer [[Carri Mundane]] (a.k.a Cassette Playa) and Steve Loveridge.<ref name="discogs" />

==Release==
In April 2007 ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' reported that ''Kala'' would be released on 26 June of that year.<ref name="mia03">{{cite web | first=Adrian|last=Covert|title=M.I.A. sets release date for upcoming album 'Kala' | url= http://www.prefixmag.com/news/mia-kala-release/9987/ | publisher = Prefix | date=10 April 2007| dateformat=dmy|accessdate=10 December 2008}}</ref>  After being delayed for unknown reasons, the album was eventually released by [[XL Recordings]] on 8 August 2007 in Japan and on 20 August in the UK, and by [[Interscope Records]] on 21 August in the United States.<ref name="grid">{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20070809112524/www.miauk.com/info/?m=200705|title=Tour Dates and News|publisher=M.I.A.|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=11 December 2008}}</ref>  The Japanese edition featured three extra tracks not included on the versions released in other countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beggarsjapan.com/artists/MIA/WPCB-10029/index.html|title=Kala|publisher=Beggars Group Japan|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref>  Following the unexpected commercial success of "Paper Planes", ''Kala'' was re-issued in the United Kingdom in October 2008.<ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.nme.com/news/mia/39504| title=MIA announces 'Paper Planes' UK release | work=[[NME]]|date=4 September 2008 | accessdate=4 February 2009|dateformat=dmy }}</ref> A 4 November 2008 U.S. re-release was announced,<ref name="reissue">{{ cite web | url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/23399805/mias_unexpected_smash | title=M.I.A.'s unexpected smash | first=Brian|last=Hiatt | work=[[Rolling Stone]]  | date=16 October 2008 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=10 October 2008 }}</ref> but as of late 2009 the album had not been re-issued in the United States.

===Promotion and accolades===
[[File:M.i.a.148.jpg|thumb|right||240px|upright|alt=A dark-skinned woman wearing a black hat and black clothing holding a microphone while performing on stage to a crowd of people.  The performance is taking place outdoors and part of a rollercoaster is visible in the background.|M.I.A. performing at the [[Siren Music Festival]] during her tour in support of the album]]
M.I.A. began her promotion of the new album with a live appearance at [[Radio 1's Big Weekend]] in [[Preston]] in May 2007, where she performed six songs from ''Kala''.<ref>{{cite web | title=Radio 1's Big Weekend : M.I.A.| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/bigweekend/2007/artists/mia/ | publisher = [[BBC]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref>  In July she began the full [[KALA Tour]] with dates in the United States before going on to play a number of [[Music festival|festivals]] in [[Europe]] and America.<ref>{{cite web | title= A globalist rapper pauses for breath| url= http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20071005a1.html| work = [[The Japan Times]]|first=Daniel|last=Robson | date=5 October 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref>  After dates in [[Asia]],<ref>{{cite web | title= M.I.A. adds U.S. dates to Summer Tour| url= http://web.archive.org/web/20080307071803/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/43913-mia-adds-us-dates-to-summer-tour| publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]] | date=28 June 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref> she returned to America for a series of shows in October and November,<ref name="miatour07">{{cite web | title= M.I.A. adds shows with The Cool Kids| url= http://web.archive.org/web/20080307034000/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/46027-mia-adds-shows-with-the-cool-kids| publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]] | date=1 October 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref> before ending the year with concerts in the UK.<ref>{{cite web | title= MIA announces new UK tour| url= http://www.nme.com/news/mia/31882| work = [[NME]] | date=18 October 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref>  The tour continued during the first half of 2008 under the banner of the [[People Vs. Money Tour]] with further dates in North America,<ref name="grid" /> although the planned European leg of the tour was eventually cancelled.<ref>{{cite web | title=M.I.A. cancels UK and European dates to garden| url= http://www.drownedinsound.com/news/3461094 | publisher = [[Drowned in Sound]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=19 December 2008|first=Ashraf|last=Dumile}}</ref>

The first track from the album to be made available to the public was "Bird Flu", which was posted on M.I.A.'s [[MySpace]] page, with an accompanying music video, in February 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2007/02/05/mias-out-for-blood-with-new-track/| title=M.I.A.<U+2019>s Out for Blood With New Track   | work = [[Rolling Stone]] | date=5 February 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=4 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.nme.com/news/mia/24472| title=MIA returns with 'Bird Flu'  | work = [[NME]] | date=27 September 2006 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=4 February 2009}}</ref>  The first official single to be lifted from the album, "Boyz", was released on 11 June 2007.<ref name="grid" /><ref>{{cite web | title= M.I.A. Namez Release Date for "Boyz" Single/USB Stick | url= http://web.archive.org/web/20071223053348/www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/43415-mia-namez-release-date-for-boyz-singleusb-stick | publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]] | date=6 June 2007|first=Matthew|last=Solarski | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref>  The second single was "Jimmy", which was released on 1 October 2007.<ref>{{cite web | title= New world order|url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2007/sep/16/urban | work = [[The Observer]]|first=Steve|last=Yates | date=16 September 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref>  The EP ''[[Paper Planes - Homeland Security Remixes EP]]'', featuring various mixes of "Paper Planes", was released digitally on 11 February 2008 and physically three weeks later.<ref name="PPHSR EP">{{cite web | url = http://web.archive.org/web/20080306224816/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/48681-dfa-adrock-remix-mias-paper-planes-on-new-ep | title =DFA, Adrock Remix M.I.A.'s "Paper Planes" on New EP |first=Paul|last=Thompson| publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=14 September 2009|date=13 February 2008 }}</ref>  A new physical single version was released in the UK on 13 October 2008.<ref name="PPRe">{{cite web | url = http://www.nme.com/news/mia/39504
 | title =MIA Announces 'Paper Planes' UK release | work = [[NME]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=17 December 2008|date=4 September 2008 }}</ref>  Also in October 2008, ''[[How Many Votes Fix Mix EP]]'' was released, containing a remix of "Boyz" with [[Jay-Z]] and the tracks "Shells" and "Far Far".<ref name="HMVFM EP">{{cite web | url = http://pitchfork.com/news/33875-mia-releases-ep-with-jay-z-version-of-boyz/ | title =M.I.A. Releases EP With Jay-Z Version of "Boyz" |first=Dave|last=Maher| publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=17 December 2008|date=28 October 2008 }}</ref>

''Kala'' achieved a high placing on most publications' end of year "best of 2007" lists, including placings at number&nbsp;8 ([[Stylus Magazine|Stylus]]<ref>{{cite web | title= Top 50 Albums of 2007|url= http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/pop_playground/top-50-albums-of-2007.htm | publisher = [[Stylus Magazine|Stylus]] | date=31 October 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref>), number&nbsp;7 (''[[NME]]''<ref>{{cite web | title= NME Albums & Tracks of the Year|url= http://www.nme.com/reviews/albums/oftheyear | work = [[NME]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref>), number&nbsp;6 (''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'',<ref>{{cite web | title= Signs of Life 2007: Best Music|url= http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2007/11/signs-of-life-2007-best-music-1.html | work = [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] | date=26 November 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref>{{cite web | title= The best music of 2007|url= http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-best-music-of-2007,2104/ | work=[[The A.V. Club]] | date=12 December 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> and ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<ref>{{cite web | title= The Best (and Worst) Albums of 2007|url= http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20162677_20164091_20166853_4,00.html | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref>), number&nbsp;4 (''[[The Guardian]]''<ref>{{cite web | title= 2007's best albums|url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2007/dec/07/4 | work = [[The Guardian]] | date=7 December 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> and ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''<ref>{{cite web | title= DiS's albums of 2007: 5<U+2013>1 (and full top 50)|url= http://www.drownedinsound.com/in_depth/2673307 | publisher = [[Drowned in Sound]] | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref>), and number&nbsp;3 ([[Pitchfork Media]]<ref>{{cite web | title= Top 50 Albums of 2007|url= http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/6753-top-50-albums-of-2007/| publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]] | date=18 December 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref>). The album was also listed at number&nbsp;3 on ''[[The Village Voice|The Village Voice's]]'' 35th annual ''[[Pazz & Jop]]'' poll.<ref name="vvmia07">{{cite web | author= | title= The 35th Annual Village Voice pazz&jop critics' poll | work=[[The Village Voice]] | url= http://web.archive.org/web/20080212030603/http://www.villagevoice.com/pazzandjop07/winners.php?type=album | date=24 January 2008| dateformat=dmy|accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref> ''[[Blender]]'' and ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' both named ''Kala'' as their number&nbsp;1 album of 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.metacritic.com/music/bests/2007.shtml | title = Best Albums of 2007 <U+2013> Music Critics' Year-End Top Ten Lists | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=17 December 2008| publisher= [[Metacritic]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17601851/the_top_50_albums_of_2007 | title = The Top 50 Albums of 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=17 December 2008|date=27 December 2007|first=Robert|last=Christgau|coauthors=Fricke, David; Hoard, Christian; Sheffield, Rob | work= [[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> "Boyz" was number&nbsp;9 and  "Shells" number&nbsp;67 on the same magazine's list of the 100 Best Songs of 2007 and 2008 respectively.<ref name="bestsongs">{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/24947047/the_100_best_singles_of_2008/17|title= The 100 Best Songs of 2008|work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=25 December 2008|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=12 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= "Rolling Stone's 100 Best Songs of 2007"| url= http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17601363/the_100_best_songs_of_2007/3 | work = [[Rolling Stone]] | date=11 December 2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=14 January 2009}}</ref>  
The album was nominated for the 2007 [[Shortlist Music Prize]].<ref name=web>{{cite web|accessdate=8 January 2010|url=http://www.shortlistofmusic.com/|title=(sh<U+00F4>rt<U+2013>l<U+012D>st)|first=Greg|last=Spotts|publisher=Short List}}</ref>  In 2009 ''NME'' placed the album at number&nbsp;72 in its list of the 100 greatest albums of the decade,<ref name="NMEGreatest">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/the-top-100-greatest-albums-of-the-decade/158049/article/158152#article|title=The Top 100 Greatest Albums of the Decade|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=4 December 2009|first=Alex|last=Miller}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' named it the ninth best album of the same period,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/31248017/100_best_albums_of_the_decade/34|title=100 Best Albums of the Decade|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=9 December 2009|accessdate=3 January 2010}}</ref> and veteran critic [[Robert Christgau]] named it the best album of the decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/list/rs00.php|title=Rolling Stone Ballot: The 00's Best Songs & Albums|publisher=[[Robert Christgau]]|accessdate=31 December 2009|date=24 December 2009}}</ref>

===Critical reaction===
{{album ratings
|rev1=[[Allmusic]] |rev1Score={{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name="AM" />
|rev2=''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' |rev2Score=(B)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20052134,00.html|title=Kala (2007)|first=Leah|last=Greenblatt|date=17 August 2007|accessdate=16 September 2009|dateformat=dmy|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref>
|rev3=''[[The Guardian]]'' |rev3Score={{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2007/aug/17/urban.electronicmusic|title=MIA, Kala|first=Alexis|last=Petridis|date=17 August 2007|accessdate=16 September 2009|dateformat=dmy|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>
|rev4=''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' |rev4Score={{Rating|4|4}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/aug/20/entertainment/et-mia20 |title=Third World beats <U+2013> M.I.A.'s latest, 'Kala,' gives voice to the voiceless, in an avant-garde mix of sounds|first=Ann|last=Powers|date=20 August 2007|accessdate=16 September 2009|dateformat=dmy|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>
|rev5=''[[NME]]'' |rev5Score=(8/10)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/mia/8949 2007|title=Mia <U+2013> Kala|first=Alex|last=Miller|date=6 September 2007|accessdate=16 September 2009|dateformat=dmy|work=[[NME]]}}</ref>
|rev6=[[Pitchfork Media]] |rev6Score=(8.9/10)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10564-kala/|title=M.I.A. <U+2013> Kala|first=Mark|last=Pytlik|date=21 August 2007|accessdate=16 September 2009|dateformat=dmy|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]}}</ref>
|rev7=[[PopMatters]] |rev7Score=(9/10)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/mia-kala|title=M.I.A.: Kala|first=Dan|last=Raper|date=20August 2007|accessdate=16 September 2009|dateformat=dmy|publisher=[[PopMatters]]}}</ref>
|rev8=''[[Rolling Stone]]'' |rev8Score={{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name="rollingstone" />
|rev9=[[Stylus Magazine|Stylus]] |rev9Score=(A)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/mia/kala.htm|title=M.I.A. <U+2013> Kala|first=Ewen|last=McGarvey|date=21 August 2007|accessdate=16 September 2009|dateformat=dmy|publisher=[[Stylus Magazine|Stylus]]}}</ref>
}}
[[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalised]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, reported an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 87 based on 37 reviews, described as "universal acclaim".<ref name="meta">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/mia/kala |title=M.I.A. : Kala (2007) |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=5 September 2007 |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |format= |work= }}</ref>  Christgau, reviewing the album for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', said that ''Kala'' "strikes deep. There's a resolute sarcasm, a weariness and defiant determination, a sense of pleasure carved out of work <U+2013> articulated by the lyrics, embodied by the music."<ref name="rollingstone">{{cite web | url= http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/15828484/review/15854428/kala | title = Kala : M.I.A. : Review : Rolling Stone |first=Robert|last=Christgau| dateformat=dmy|accessdate=23 December 2007|date=23 August 2007 | work= [[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>  Eric R. Danton of ''[[The Hartford Courant]]'' called ''Kala'' "[[pop music]] without the vapidity, and [[Music and politics|political music]] without the condescension."<ref>{{cite web | url= http://web.archive.org/web/20071113234739/http://www.courant.com/entertainment/music/reviews/albums/hc-topcd0823.artaug23,0,3313809.story|date=23 August 2007|first=Eric R.|last=Danton | title = Kala by M.I.A. <U+2013> Politics With A Strong Beat | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=23 December 2007 | work= [[The Hartford Courant]]}}</ref>  ''[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]'', in a positive review, noted that ''Kala'' "not only doesn't disappoint, it renews faith in M.I.A. and confirms her commitment to the individualistic sound she has created."<ref>{{cite article|title=M.I.A.: Kala|work=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]] |date=Summer 2007|page=74}}</ref>  Conversely, ''Dusted'''s Ben Tausig described the album as "inconclusive" and said it "plays as mixed media pastiche".<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/3778|date=20 August 2007|first=Ben|last=Tausig | title = Dusted Reviews | dateformat=dmy|accessdate=18 December 2008 | work= Dusted}}</ref>  ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' said "the majority of ''Kala''...is limp and unfocussed."<ref name="vibe">{{cite article|title=M.I.A. : Kala|date=September 2007|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|page=133}}</ref>  Writing in ''NME'', Alex Miller acknowledged that M.I.A.'s music polarised opinion, claiming that some members of the magazine's staff had "fed several copies [of the album] into the shredder claiming aural abuse", but went on to praise the album for its innovation and refer to it as the artist's masterpiece.<ref name="NMEGreatest" />

===Commercial performance===
As of February 2009, ''Kala'' had sold over 440,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filter-mag.com/index.php?id=18400&c=1|title=Chart Rundown: Franz Ferdinand, Bon Iver
|dateformat=5 February 2009|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=7 February 209|work=[[Filter (magazine)|Filter]]}}</ref>  The album debuted at number&nbsp;18 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, selling about 29,000 copies in its first week.<ref name="miakalasales">{{cite news |last=Hasty|first= Katie|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080204000923/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003632746|title= 'High School Musical 2' Hangs On Atop Billboard 200 |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=14 September 2009 |work=[[Billboard]] |format= |publisher= }}</ref>  It failed to rise above this position but still significantly outperformed the peak position of 190 attained by M.I.A.'s previous album.<ref name="Amgmiach">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusicguide.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:jg6gtq4zzu47~T5|title=M.I.A. <U+2013> Charts & Awards|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=7 March 2010|dateformat=dmy}}</ref>   It also topped the [[Dance/Electronic Albums|Top Electronic Albums]] chart.<ref name="BB1" />  In the [[UK Albums Chart]] it debuted at number&nbsp;39,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/top40_albums_last.php?week=75&end=26/08/2007%20-%2001/09/2007|title=Top 40 Albums Archive :: Week 35 : 26/08/2007<U+2013>01/09/2007|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=3 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref> and again did not rise above this position, although as in the US this represented an improvement on the chart performance of ''Arular'', which had peaked at number&nbsp;98.<ref name="zob">{{cite book|title=The Virgin Book of British Hit Albums|last=Roach|first=Martin|publisher=Virgin Books|isbn=0-7535-1700-0|year=2009|page=328}}</ref>  The album also reached the top 40 in a number of other countries.<ref name="swedishcharts" />

